  "prompt": "Differentiate a^x up to 4 terms?",
  "response": "To differentiate \\(a^x\\) with respect to \\(x\\), we use the fact that \\(a^x = e^{x \\ln(a)}\\). Let's proceed step-by-step:\n\n1. **First Derivative:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx} a^x = \\frac{d}{dx} e^{x \\ln(a)} = e^{x \\ln(a)} \\cdot \\ln(a) = a^x \\ln(a)\n   \\]\n\n2. **Second Derivative:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^2}{dx^2} a^x = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x \\ln(a)) = \\ln(a) \\frac{d}{dx} a^x = \\ln(a) \\cdot a^x \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^2\n   \\]\n\n3. **Third Derivative:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^3}{dx^3} a^x = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x (\\ln(a))^2) = (\\ln(a))^2 \\frac{d}{dx} a^x = (\\ln(a))^2 \\cdot a^x \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^3\n   \\]\n\n4. **Fourth Derivative:**\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d^4}{dx^4} a^x = \\frac{d}{dx} (a^x (\\ln(a))^3) = (\\ln(a))^3 \\frac{d}{dx} a^x = (\\ln(a))^3 \\cdot a^x \\ln(a) = a^x (\\ln(a))^4\n   \\]\n\nSo, the first four derivatives of \\(a^x\\) are:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} a^x = a^x \\ln(a)\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{d^2}{dx^2} a^x = a^x (\\ln(a))^2\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{d^3}{dx^3} a^x = a^x (\\ln(a))^3\n\\]\n\\[\n\\frac{d^4}{dx^4} a^x = a^x (\\ln(a))^4\n\\]",
